commit.message: Increase version to 0.5.2
Make the MSYS instructions arch-neutral

Show usage message in msgbox on Windows

As the process is GUI one, it doesn't have stderr console and can't show
any wxCmdLineParser output there.

Switch Windows build to 64bit binaries

Use the x86_64 compiler instead of i686 and use the version that uses
UCRT runtime. This is available by default on Windows 10 or newer and
can be installed on older OSes too.
Increase version to 0.5.1
Merge branch 'github-actions'

Significantly speed up collect-dlls.sh

Don't re-run objdump repeatedly. Cache the results instead and only run
it once per executable file.

Switch to GitHub Actions for CI

Remove AppVeyor config, replace with equivalent GitHub Actions.

Adds a per page pixel difference tolerance option

This option, if specified and greater than zero will cause the
application to return a non-zero status if any page has more pixel
changes than the value of per-page-pixel-tolerance

This can be used with channel-tolerance. Only pixels that exceed the
channel-tolerance will be counted.

Start gitignore comments on their own lines

According to the git documentation, comments must begin on the first
character of a line. See https://git-scm.com/docs/gitignore:

A line starting with # serves as a comment.
Add Chocolatey install instructions
Reflect renaming of package from Ubuntu 20.10 on
Increase version to v0.5

Add --grayscale option

When used, converts the diff output to grayscale and only uses color
for pixels with differences. This is useful for comparing documents
that use colors and that may look confusing in the diff view.
Show default DPI value used in --help output

Remove code for old versions of glib and wxWidgets

Remove support code for ancient version of glib and wxWidgets libraries.

Follow-up to 8a936f8d263b06191b6163d796ed4b03b21aec60
Tiny code formatting fixes

Add rasterization DPI option (#71)

Introduce command-line option --dpi to ignore small differences. 
Smaller DPI can be used to ignore tiny differences when combined with 
channel-tolerance.
